panel-1.panelText: The ability to start a task independently, the self-starter. It means taking charge before others do, without being prompted by anyone but you.

panel-2.panelText: Over the chessboard, this ties in with planning. Always know what your plan is and how you are going to implement. If you’re on the attack and your opponent tries to launch their own, who’s attack is more important?

panel-3.panelText: Jeremy Silman spoke best about it: initiative is how you view your standing over the psychological manifestation of the board of chess (and life). Push your agenda, champion it in favor of your opponents.

panel-4.panelText: So… Will you accept your own call to action, and grab ahold of the wheel on the metaphorical car of life?

panel-1.panelText: Decisions: the tangible application of the parallels between you and chess. You must do this every turn and every time. No matter what happens around you, if you’re reading this you have made and will make decisions, big or small.

panel-2.panelText: Many of these thought motifs and mindsets revolve around this concept. Reflection, present-moment analysis: they will determine what path you choose.

panel-3.panelText: Sometimes our emotions and thoughts lead us down unfavorable paths. Even though that may be an ‘incorrect’ path, we will have more chances to make favorable decisions.

panel-4.panelText: Understand that decisions come with consequences. Good or bad, they are inevitable with any decision you make. Cause and effect. Thinking ahead comes into play here when you ask yourself: “what are the consequences of this decision?”.

panel-5.panelText: You are living your own choose your own story book. Adjust your sails and make beautiful choices.

panel-1.panelText: More about Pawns. Depending on the position they we attain different names or labels, much like good and bad Bishops.

panel-2.panelText: The first type is called the isolated Pawn. Pawns operate well next to each other. In the instance that a Pawn is attacked, they may advance a square and be protected by their neighbor. Sometimes when trades happen, a Pawn will lose both of its neighbors and no longer has any chance of protection.

panel-3.panelText: The isolated Pawn is not always weak. In many variations, a Queen’s Pawn may be isolated. Though not protected, it may help control central or key squares and it also means you have two open files for major pieces to operate on.

panel-4.panelText: Doubled Pawns are similar. It happens when there are two Pawns on a file and there’s a better chance they are both isolated. These Pawns should be treated similarly: take advantage of the squares they control and the open files they create. If you need to recapture with a Pawn (doubling them) then the rule of thumb is to capture towards the center of the board. There are exceptions, however. Capturing this way opens up the Bishop’s eyes.

panel-5.panelText: Be careful of either of these Pawn types. You may find instances to isolate or double your opponents Pawn. You may decide to do this, then you can trade down to an endgame with a slight edge.

panel-6.panelText: Be careful of either of these Pawn types. You may find instances to isolate or double your opponents Pawn. You may decide to do this, then you can trade down to an endgame with an slight edge.

panel-7.panelText: Be careful of either of these Pawn types. You may find instances to isolate or double your opponents Pawn. You may decide to do this, then you can trade down to an endgame with an slight edge.

panel-8.panelText: The last type is important: the passed Pawn. This is a Pawn that has no opposing-colored Pawn in front of it, on either adjacent file. Therefore there is a low chance of it being traded off in an equal exchange. Protect these Pawns with your life and push them down the board towards promotion. They are worth much more than a single point and are often a decisive winning advantage.

panel-9.panelText: Pawn types are good to understand when evaluating a position. Keep in mind how you’re protecting them and your pieces. We’ll talk more about Pawn structures later where you can see these labeled Pawns in action.

lesson-4.title: Rooks
lesson-4.nodeText: Open your lines and centralize as we cover intermediate

panel-1.panelText: Let’s talk about Rooks. As a major piece and slider they have access to every square on the board, in a predictable and powerful manner.

panel-2.panelText: In the principles discussion, it’s encouraged to connect them by developing all your other pieces and castling. Then what? At that point we expect there have been a few Pawns traded off. The most basic form of plan for Rook placement is along a file that doesn’t have any Pawns on it, known as an open file. Even if your opponent has a Pawn on that file (half-open) it might still be a good idea with the possibility of taking it later on.

panel-3.panelText: Once on a file like this, the Rook has more scope to be lifted, to be moved to a more active rank with lateral movement with chance at contributing to an attack.

panel-4.panelText: The second side effect of this vertical Rook movement on an open file is that it prepares for the second Rook to join that same file. The power of two Rooks down an open file can be a decisive advantage if you know what to do next.

panel-5.panelText: With two supported Rooks along an open file what do you do next? Penetrate your opponent’s position. Depending on the position if you adversary is holding their position well you move your Rook to the 7th or 8th rank if you’re white (2nd or 1st if you’re black). The second to last rank can be a vulnerable spot, look at all the Pawns for the taking. Look at the Pawns you can attack that are guarding your opponent’s King!

panel-6.panelText: Consider the last few steps if you’re looking for something productive to do with your position. Make sure you read the position, create the open files.

panel-7.panelText: 7th rank is a good spot, but if you can go for the King, do it. Here the black player failed to push any Pawns in front their King. They are vulnerable to a back-rank mate. Follow the sequence and observe the Pawns that cut off the King for a Rook to land a final blow.

panel-8.panelText: 7th rank is a good spot, but if you can go for the King, do it. Here the black player failed to push any Pawns in front their King. They are vulnerable to a back-rank mate. Follow the sequence and observe the Pawns that cut off the King for a Rook to land a final blow.

panel-9.panelText: 7th rank is a good spot, but if you can go for the King, do it. Here the black player failed to push any Pawns in front their King. They are vulnerable to a back-rank mate. Follow the sequence and observe the Pawns that cut off the King for a Rook to land a final blow.

panel-10.panelText: 7th rank is a good spot, but if you can go for the King, do it. Here the black player failed to push any Pawns in front their King. They are vulnerable to a back-rank mate. Follow the sequence and observe the Pawns that cut off the King for a Rook to land a final blow.

panel-11.panelText: Rooks aren’t only good for attacking. If the position is let’s say closed or there are no obvious Pawn breaks to open up the file we discussed, don’t be afraid to let your Rook defend the base of a Pawn chain (weaknesses are explained later on). Here we see the Rook providing support to a stable Pawn chain.

panel-12.panelText: We mentioned passed Pawns in the previous lesson. If you have a Rook lying around this late in the game, the only correct placement is behind the Pawn. If the Rook is behind or to the side of the Pawn you will have to keep moving to continue support or leave space for promotion.

panel-13.panelText: Finally, another endgame consideration and reminder, as with all other pieces, foster activity for your pieces. Activity, scope, mobility, just make sure your piece can move to more squares to help with attack, defense, or tactics.

lesson-5.title: Space
lesson-5.nodeText: Space is a physical realization of the chessboard where pieces can be mobile.

panel-1.panelText: Space is a built in mechanic of the chessboard. Each of the 64 squares represents a piece of it. That you want to control. The more space you have the better your chance of converting to an endgame with a Pawn that is fast to promote. Army to begin the game is confined to this close-quarter zone, each cornered against a hypothetical wall.

panel-2.panelText: Pawns are the main definition of how much space a player controls. You push all your Pawns forward, you control more space. But at what cost?

panel-3.panelText: A popular concept taught is establish a Pawn duo in the center. The leading side effect is having space to move your pieces. However, in some scenarios like this one the Pawns have advanced to far for their own good and have created weaknesses that they can no longer go back to defend upon. White has space, but their Pawns do not control the center.

panel-4.panelText: When dealing with abundance or lack of space, the plans for each player is clear. if you’re the player with less space, a good bet is to trade off pieces and initiate pawn breaks. On the other hand if you have the space, keep pieces on the board. Your pieces have activity and the time and ability to decide upon a plan of attack, while your opponent has little activity and no choice but to wait out defeat.

lesson-6.title: Coordination
lesson-6.nodeText: On the outside, chess is a singular-minded game. Warlords clashing it out against one another. On the inside it's a team sport. Let's find out why.

panel-1.panelText: Chess may only be a 1 vs 1 game, but at the core it is built on team work. Pieces must work together and coordinate in order to win. What does this mean really? As always it depends on what position is in front of you, but we will break it down into two parts.

panel-2.panelText: Defense. As covered in tactics, this is essential to avoiding quick, short-term tactical blunders. Before a move, ask yourself: are my pieces defended adequately? How can I solidify the integrity of my position before justifying an attack? Should I trade off a piece that is poorly defended?

panel-3.panelText: Convergence. A different way of say attack, but this is more realized when identifying what pieces or squares they can move two, specifically the same squares. Once you threaten an enemy piece or square with two pieces, one will be supported upon a capture or move. This may be a significant advantage.

panel-4.panelText: To apply convergence, you will need to apply your ability to think ahead and pick out what squares will be important. Are there any Pawn breaks you should be anticipating? How about open diagonals that a Bishop can contribute along? Answering these questions might help you identify your next move, even if it means spending a tempo to ‘redeploy’ your Knight to stand upon a wealthy outpost.

panel-5.panelText: A basic example that you will see players try to pull off in the opening if f7. This is a weakness in black’s (f2 in white’s) camp. You’ll see the Queen work together with the Knight or Bishop often to pull off convergence like these. Ask yourself: “what is a key square can my pieces work together to attack? How do I achieve this objective?”.

lesson-7.title: Patterns I
lesson-7.nodeText: The fianchetto, open lines, and batteries.

panel-1.panelText: Let’s cover a few more patterns. Normally we develop our bishops by moving our center Pawns. This is another way called the ‘fianchetto’.

panel-2.panelText: Develop your Knight first as usual.

panel-3.panelText: Move your g Pawn one square forward.

panel-4.panelText: Then, your Bishop gets tucked within this Pawn structure. When playing as black, this setup is called “King’s Indian Defense”. It allows your opponent to capture the center with Pawns, but if you look closely the Bishop and Knight observe the center from afar. This is known as a hypermodern opening.

panel-5.panelText: Lets talk about open lines. These can be files, diagonals, and even ranks. It is very important to give your sliders (any Rook or Bishop pattern pieces including Queen) many squares to move to in to thrive and have good activity.

panel-6.panelText: With open lines and activity comes resourcefulness and access into your opponents territory, their Pawn weaknesses, and their King. Treat this as a side quest, another objective to achieve during your match. Identify your good Bishop and where the Pawn breaks will occur. These are where your sliders should operate.

panel-7.panelText: On open lines we have a semi-tactic called the battery. Place a Queen (typically in front of) a Rook or Bishop. Your opponent will have to rush to the defense of a key square. You may even get lucky and pull off a quick checkmate with one. Be careful if your opponent tries to build one though, this can be a long-ranged attack.

panel-8.panelText: Keep making observations about what’s going on on the board. It’s an unfolding story. There are many patterns to watch for, be on the lookout!
